Here is a complete guide and a ready-to-use GitHub-flavored Markdown text that covers Kubernetes Liveness, Readiness, and Startup probes using httpGet, exec, and tcpSocket.
To make this practical, the examples are structured around a classic Three-Tier Architecture:
	1	Frontend Tier (Using httpGet)
	2	Backend API Tier (Using exec`)
	3	Database Tier (Using tcpSocket)
At the bottom, you'll find the exact imperative commands to generate and run these quickly without writing YAML from scratch.
Kubernetes Probes in a Three-Tier Architecture
This guide demonstrates how to implement the three types of probes (Startup, Readiness, and Liveness) across three different tiers using three different mechanisms (httpGet, exec, and tcpSocket).
[ Frontend Tier ]  --> Uses httpGet (Checks web UI paths)
       |
[ Backend API Tier ] --> Uses exec (Runs custom health-check scripts)
       |
[ Database Tier ]    --> Uses tcpSocket (Checks if DB port is open)
1. Frontend Tier (Using httpGet)
The frontend tier typically serves web content. We use httpGet to ensure the web server is responding to HTTP requests.
	•	Startup Probe: Gives the web server 30 seconds to start up.
	•	Readiness Probe: Checks if the /ready static page is accessible before routing user traffic.
	•	Liveness Probe: Periodically hits /healthz to ensure the server hasn't crashed.
YAML

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: frontend-tier
  labels:
    tier: frontend
spec:
  containers:
   Tir- name: web-app
    image: nginx:alpine
    ports:
    - containerPort: 80
    
    # 1. Startup Probe
    startupProbe:
      httpGet:
        path: /index.html
        port: 80
      failureThreshold: 6
      periodSeconds: 5 # Gives it up to 30s to start
      
    # 2. Readiness Probe
    readinessProbe:
      httpGet:
        path: /ready
        port: 80
      initialDelaySeconds: 5
      periodSeconds: 5
      
    # 3. Liveness Probe
    livenessProbe:
      httpGet:
        path: /healthz
        port: 80
      initialDelaySeconds: 10
      periodSeconds: 10
2. Backend API Tier (Using exec)
The backend app might need to run an internal script, check a local file, or run a CLI tool to verify its internal state. We use exec commands here.
	•	Startup Probe: Checks if a boot lockfile has been cleared.
	•	Readiness Probe: Executes a custom python/bash script to check database connectivity.
	•	Liveness Probe: Checks if the application process PID is still active.
YAML

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: backend-tier
  labels:
    tier: backend
spec:
  containers:
  - name: api-app
    image: python:3.9-slim
    command: ["/bin/sh", "-c", "touch /tmp/started; sleep 9999"]
    
    # 1. Startup Probe
    startupProbe:
      exec:
        command:
        - cat
        - /tmp/started
      failureThreshold: 3
      periodSeconds: 5
      
    # 2. Readiness Probe
    readinessProbe:
      exec:
        command:
        - /bin/sh
        - -c
        - "python -c 'import urllib.request; urllib.request.urlopen(\"http://localhost:8080/ready-check\")'"
      initialDelaySeconds: 5
      periodSeconds: 10
      
    # 3. Liveness Probe
    livenessProbe:
      exec:
        command:
        - kill
        - -0
        - "1" # Checks if PID 1 is alive
      initialDelaySeconds: 15
      periodSeconds: 20
3. Database Tier (Using tcpSocket)
For databases or message queues (like MySQL, PostgreSQL, or Redis), checking if the TCP port is open and accepting connections is often the fastest and most reliable baseline check.
	•	Startup Probe: Waits for the heavy DB engine to open its networking port.
	•	Readiness Probe: Ensures the port is open to accept connection pools from the backend.
	•	Liveness Probe: Continuously monitors if the port goes down (indicating a crash).
YAML

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: database-tier
  labels:
    tier: database
spec:
  containers:
  - name: db-mysql
    image: mysql:8.0
    env:
    - name: MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD
      value: "secretpass"
    ports:
    - containerPort: 3306
    
    # 1. Startup Probe
    startupProbe:
      tcpSocket:
        port: 3306
      failureThreshold: 10
      periodSeconds: 5 # Gives the DB 50 seconds to initialize schemas
      
    # 2. Readiness Probe
    readinessProbe:
      tcpSocket:
        port: 3306
      initialDelaySeconds: 5
      periodSeconds: 5
      
    # 3. Liveness Probe
    livenessProbe:
      tcpSocket:
        port: 3306
      initialDelaySeconds: 15
      periodSeconds: 10
The Imperative Way (Fast Commands)
While you cannot generate all three complex probes simultaneously inside a single kubectl run command string, the fastest imperative way to create these templates without manual writing is to generate the base YAML via --dry-run=client and redirect it to a file.
Here are the exact commands to generate these instantly:
1. Generate Frontend (HTTP) Base:
Bash

kubectl run frontend-tier --image=nginx:alpine --port=80 --dry-run=client -o yaml > frontend.yaml
(Open frontend.yaml and paste the livenessProbe/readinessProbe blocks under the container specs).
2. Generate Backend (Exec) Base:
Bash

kubectl run backend-tier --image=python:3.9-slim --dry-run=client -o yaml > backend.yaml
3. Generate Database (TCP) Base & Run Immediately:
If you just want to run a quick test pod imperatively with a basic basic probe mechanism directly from the CLI, use:
Bash

# Imperative creation of a pod with a basic Liveness HTTP check
kubectl run test-http-pod --image=nginx --port=80 --liveness-handler='{"httpGet": {"path": "/", "port": 80}}'

# Imperative creation of a pod with a basic Liveness Exec check
kubectl run test-exec-pod --image=busybox --command -- sh -c "sleep 3600" --liveness-handler='{"exec": {"command": ["cat", "/tmp/healthy"]}}'
